Subject: Cost Differential for Enterprise Merchants - Payment Depot Pricing
Bill-
I've spoken with a few folks internally and want to provide some color on the topic, especially regarding the Card Connect clawback:
Regarding the Card Connect clawback:
• I don't see it that way. I don't believe large merchants generating 5 mil or more per year get boarding bonuses. So there is no risk to claw that back. Even if there was language that there could be claw back for that reason, it is not
11
enforceable.
Regarding Payment Depot:
• I can match all Payment Depot pricing except for the $500k per month merchants. Payment Depot charges $ .25 per transaction for those accounts, I don't cover any costs for those merchants, no pci, no software, no equipment. Those $500k per month merchants would cost me more money.
What I can match is the pricing for merchants that are processing between $50k and $500k per month. For these merchants I charge the $79 fee, match interchange and provide free equipment, pci, software.
Regarding the 300-400 merchants processing millions of dollars per month that get sent to Payment Depot:
• We're not going to provide the capital necessary to convert these merchants back.
•
What I suggest is that FAP and Shift 4 start approving those types of merchants on the merchant agreement that I have
provided. Merchant's over 50k a month and less than SOOk per month, get the same structure as payment depot.
I have a boardable merchant right now for you, that is at $80k per month in processing volume. I am happy to set an example for you of how we can conduct business in a fashion similar to Payment Depot.
Best Regards,
Todd
